== Tips for creating screencasts ==

* ScreencastMode (everywhere, but only inside Emacs) and ScreencastRecord (GNU/Linux, FreeBSD - ogg, ie only open formats) are modes for creating screencasts from within Emacs easily.
* Derek Slager used CommandLogMode (everywhere, but only inside Emacs) to create a screencast.
* See also [http://www.debugmode.com/wink/ wink] (freeware w32, creates flash video, is it ok to link to it here? An open source version is on its [http://groups.google.com/group/wink-discuss/browse_thread/thread/42812132e43573a0 way].)
* A post describing how the screencasts on the emacsmovies.org website are done. - http://emacsmovies.org/blog/2012/01/21/welcome_to_emacsmovies.org/
* NicFerrier records ogg files with RecordMyDesktop on Ubuntu and tries to do it in a single take
** then he uploads the ogg to youtube
*** Youtube generate a whole bunch of alternative sizes without having to edit at all
* Use a hi-res screen and then make a smallish window that you record - then you can have your script in a bigger window to one side.
* Use a clean Emacs instance to do recordings, so you can prove that something will work for someone else.
* Try and start the screencast with your voice being enthusiastic! people listen to the first 30seconds.

== Ideas for screencasts ==

You don't have to be an expert in order to share what you've learned. Please consider contributing a screencast! You could save people time and introduce people to neat workflows. Here are some ideas for things to talk about:

* Lists of ideas
** [https://emacsconf.github.io/emacsconf2015/ Notes from EmacsConf 2015 brainstorming]
** [http://emacsnyc.org/giving-a-talk.html EmacsNYC talk suggestions]
** See also: [SachaChua Sacha]'s [http://sachachua.com/blog/2013/04/brainstorming-ways-to-help-build-the-emacs-community/ community building ideas].
* Specific requests
** [InternetRelayChat IRC]ing in Emacs - demoing the popular clients and introducing [EmacsChannel #emacs].

